  "course_description": "Topic changes to meet current interest of students and faculty. Course may be repeated for credit as topic varies.",
  "course_notes": "(Same as ANT 385 3) (Complete Topic - Witchcraft and Magic: Ritual,Power, and Social Identities) (This course explores the evidence for two modalities of ritual power in the ancient Mediterranean - witchcraft and magic - which lay beyond the boundaries of civic ritual and festivals. Our analyses will build on ethnographic studies of these practices in living cultures, and archaeological, art historical, and literary sources from Greece and Rome - curse tablets and amulets, love spells, poisons, and charms to protect the crops and calm the seas. The terrifying mythic figures Medea, Circe, Canidia and Erichtho will be used to explore the historical evidence for women charged with the use of these powers.)",
